COVID-19 Data Mining¶

Task: Find the importance of government responses to COVID-19

Jupyter Notebook:

  • Business Understanding
  • Data Understanding
  • Data Preparation
  • Modeling

1. Business Understanding¶

The rapid spread of COVID-19 globally has created a wide range of responses from governments. Common measures include school closings, travel restrictions, bans on public gatherings, emergency investments in healthcare facilities, new forms of social welfare provision, contact tracing and other interventions to contain the spread of the virus, augment health systems, and manage the economic consequences of these actions. However, governments have varied substantially—both across countries, and often within countries—in the measures that they have adopted and how quickly they have adopted them. This variation has created debate as policymakers and publics deliberate over the level of response that should be pursued and how quickly to implement them or roll them back, and as public health experts learn in real time the measures that are more or less effective. (Petherick, 2020)

1.1. The Oxford COVID-19 Government Response Tracker¶

The Oxford COVID-19 Government Response Tracker (OxCGRT) provides a systematic cross-national, cross-temporal measure to understand how government responses have evolved over the full period of the disease’s spread. The project tracks governments’ policies and interventions across a standardized series of indicators and creates a suite of composites indices to measure the extent of these responses. Data is collected and updated in real time by a team of over one hundred Oxford students, alumni and staff, and project partners. (Petherick, 2020)

1.2. Data¶

The data is collected from publicly available information by a cross-disciplinary Oxford University team of academics and students from every part of the world, led by the Blavatnik School of Government. We collate publicly available information on a number of indicators of government response. (OxCGRT, 2020)

2. Data Understanding¶

2.1. Features¶

Containment and closure¶

  • C1 School closing - Ordinal
  • C2 Workplace closing - Ordinal
  • C3 Cancel public events - Ordinal
  • C4 Restrictions on gathering size - Ordinal
  • C5 Close public transport - Ordinal
  • C6 Stay at home requirements - Ordinal
  • C7 Restrictions on internal movement - Ordinal
  • C8 Restrictions on international travel - Ordinal

Economic response¶

  • E1 income support - Ordinal
  • E2 debt/contract relief for households - Ordinal
  • E3 fiscal measures - Numeric
  • E4 giving international support - Numeric

Health systems¶

  • H1 Public information campaign - Ordinal
  • H2 Testing policy - Ordinal
  • H3 Contact tracing - Ordinal
  • H4 Emergency investment in healthcare - Numeric
  • H5 Investment in Covid-19 vaccines - Numeric
  • H6 Facial coverings - Ordinal

Miscellaneous¶

  • Other responses - Text

2.2. Indicators¶

  • Ordinal indicators measure policies on a simple scale of severity / intensity. These indicators are reported for each day a policy is in place. Many have a further flag to note if they are “targeted”, applying only to a sub-region of a jurisdiction, or a specific sector; or “general”, applying throughout that jurisdiction or across the economy. (Petherick, 2020)
  • Numeric indicators measure a specific number, typically the value in USD. These indicators are only reported on the day they are announced. (Petherick, 2020)

2.3. Predictors¶

As predictors just the features used for counting of 'strigency factor' (Petherick, 2020) are used. The other features do not have direct impact on reduction of new COVID cases. These predictors are used:

  • C1 School closing - Ordinal
  • C2 Workplace closing - Ordinal
  • C3 Cancel public events - Ordinal
  • C4 Restrictions on gathering size - Ordinal
  • C5 Close public transport - Ordinal
  • C6 Stay at home requirements - Ordinal
  • C7 Restrictions on internal movement - Ordinal
  • C8 Restrictions on international travel - Ordinal
  • H1 Public information campaign - Ordinal

2.4. Import CSV¶

  • The file is from this address: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/OxCGRT/covid-policy-tracker/master/data/OxCGRT_latest.csv
  • Data imported on the 10th of February 2021

3. Data Preparation¶

3.1. Remove last 2 days¶

Last 2 days removed because of a lot of missing values.

In [10]:
data = data[data.Date < pd.Timestamp('2021-02-08')]

Just EU countries¶

In [11]:
eu_countries = [
    'AUT',
    'BEL',

3.2. Country and Region to CountryRegionCode¶

Some countries are separated to regions (for example states in USA). Unique values need to be generated by merging country names and region names.

In [12]:
data['CountryRegionCode'] = data['CountryCode'].add(data['RegionCode'], fill_value='')

3.3. Remove all CountryRegionCodes where more than 70 missing values for ConfirmedDeaths or ConfirmedCases¶

It reduces dataset from 72171 rows to 41454 rows.

In [13]:
data = data.groupby('CountryRegionCode').filter(lambda s: s['ConfirmedCases'].isnull().sum() <= 70)
data = data.groupby('CountryRegionCode').filter(lambda s: s['ConfirmedDeaths'].isnull().sum() <= 70)

3.4. Missing values¶

Interpolate values in forward direction. Then missing values in the beginnings of epochs replace with 0. It needs to be done for each combination of country and region.

Targets¶

In [14]:
original_targets = ['ConfirmedCases', 'ConfirmedDeaths']
for reg_code in data['CountryRegionCode'].unique():
    data.update(data[data['CountryRegionCode'] == reg_code][original_targets].interpolate(method ='linear', limit_direction ='forward').fillna(0))

3.5. Merge Measure and Flag¶

Flag explains if the closure was applied in general (1) or just locally (0). In this section new features are created from the measure and its flag. For example the features 'C1_School closing' and 'C1_Flag' are transfered to two new features: 'C1_School closing_local' and 'C1_School closing_general'.

In [20]:
merging_couples = {}
for predictor in predictors:
    code = predictor[:2]
    if code not in merging_couples:
        merging_couples[code] = [predictor]
    else:
        merging_couples[code].append(predictor)
for key, couple in dict(merging_couples).items():
    if len(couple) < 2:
        del merging_couples[key]
merging_couples
Out[20]:
{'C1': ['C1_School closing', 'C1_Flag'],
 'C2': ['C2_Workplace closing', 'C2_Flag'],
 'C3': ['C3_Cancel public events', 'C3_Flag'],
 'C4': ['C4_Restrictions on gatherings', 'C4_Flag'],
 'C5': ['C5_Close public transport', 'C5_Flag'],
 'C6': ['C6_Stay at home requirements', 'C6_Flag'],
 'C7': ['C7_Restrictions on internal movement', 'C7_Flag'],
 'H1': ['H1_Public information campaigns', 'H1_Flag']}
In [21]:
for couple in merging_couples.values():
    predictors.remove(couple[0])
    predictors.remove(couple[1])
    col_name = couple[0] + '_general'
    data[col_name] = data[couple[0]]
    data.loc[data[couple[1]] != 1, col_name] = 0
    predictors.append(col_name)
    col_name = couple[0] + '_local'
    data[col_name] = data[couple[0]]
    data.loc[data[couple[1]] == 1, col_name] = 0
    predictors.append(col_name)
data

data['RegionName'] = data['RegionName'].fillna('basic')
data_weather = None
for country in data['CountryName'].unique():
    if country == 'Eswatini':
            country = 'Kingdom of Eswatini'
    for region in data[data['CountryName'] == country]['RegionName'].unique():
        if region != 'basic':
            country_data = pd.read_csv(urllib.parse.quote(country + ', ' + region) + ".csv", parse_dates=[0], header=0) 
        else:
            country_data = pd.read_csv(urllib.parse.quote(country) + ".csv", parse_dates=[0], header=0) 
        country_data = country_data[country_data["date_time"] < pd.Timestamp('2021-02-08')] # time limit
        new_country_cols = []
        for col in country_data.columns:
            new_country_cols.append(col.split('_', 1)[1])
        country_data.columns = new_country_cols
        origin_data = data[(data['CountryName'] == country) & (data['RegionName'] == region)]
        country_data.index = origin_data.index
        data_country_weather = pd.concat([origin_data, country_data.reindex(origin_data.index)], axis=1)
        if type(data_weather) == type(None):
             data_weather = data_country_weather
        else:
            data_weather = data_weather.append(data_country_weather)
data_weather

3.7. Target Preparation¶

Percent change in daily increases of new cases or deaths.

In the data the target data is comulative. This operations need to be taken:

Calculate daily increase. Difference between day+1 and day. Calculate percent change between daily increase and last 7 days average.

In [30]:
data['ConfirmedCasesDaily'] = data.groupby('CountryRegionCode')['ConfirmedCases'].diff()
data['ConfirmedDeathsDaily'] = data.groupby('CountryRegionCode')['ConfirmedDeaths'].diff()

for i in range(1,8):
    data['ConfirmedCasesDailyDayBefore' + str(i)] = data.groupby('CountryRegionCode')['ConfirmedCasesDaily'].shift(i)
    data['ConfirmedDeathsDailyDayBefore' + str(i)] = data.groupby('CountryRegionCode')['ConfirmedDeathsDaily'].shift(i)
   
def sum_cases(row):
    sum_values = 0
    for i in range(1,8):
        if str(row['ConfirmedCasesDailyDayBefore' + str(i)]) != 'nan':
            sum_values = sum_values + row['ConfirmedCasesDailyDayBefore' + str(i)] 
    return sum_values / 7

def sum_deaths(row):
    sum_values = 0
    for i in range(1,8):
        if str(row['ConfirmedDeathsDailyDayBefore' + str(i)]) != 'nan':
            sum_values = sum_values + row['ConfirmedDeathsDailyDayBefore' + str(i)]  
    return sum_values / 7
    
data['Last7DaysAvgCases'] = data.apply(sum_cases, axis=1)
data['Last7DaysAvgDeaths'] = data.apply(sum_deaths, axis=1)

def pct_change_cases(row):
    #return row["ConfirmedCasesDaily"] - row["Last7DaysAvgCases"]
    if row["ConfirmedCasesDaily"] == 0:
        return 0
    if row["Last7DaysAvgCases"] == 0:
        return 1
    return row["ConfirmedCasesDaily"]/(row["Last7DaysAvgCases"]) - 1

def pct_change_deaths(row):
    #return row["ConfirmedDeathsDaily"] - row["Last7DaysAvgDeaths"]
    if row["ConfirmedDeathsDaily"] == 0:
        return 0
    if row["Last7DaysAvgDeaths"] == 0:
        return 1
    return row["ConfirmedDeathsDaily"]/(row["Last7DaysAvgDeaths"]) - 1

data['ConfirmedCasesPctChange'] = data.apply(pct_change_cases, axis=1)
data['ConfirmedDeathsPctChange'] = data.apply(pct_change_deaths, axis=1)

data = data.dropna(subset=['ConfirmedCasesDailyDayBefore7', 'ConfirmedDeathsDailyDayBefore7']) # Drop all which do not have a value fo the largest shift

3.8. Discretize target¶

The daily percent change is transfered to 5 categories:

  • High increase (1.5 to infinity)
  • Low increase (1 to 1.5>
  • No increase <1>
  • Low decrease <0.5 to 1)
  • High decrease (-infinity to 0.5)
In [31]:
condition = lambda x: 'High increase' if x > 0.5 else ('Low increase' if x > 0 else ('High decrease' if x < - 0.5 else ('Low decrease' if x < 0 else 'No increase')))
data['ConfirmedCasesPctChangeCat'] = data['ConfirmedCasesPctChange'].apply(condition)
data['ConfirmedDeathsPctChangeCat'] = data['ConfirmedDeathsPctChange'].apply(condition)

3.9. Discretise to ordinal target¶

it is needed for calculation of time shift.

In [36]:
conditionOrdinal = lambda x: 4 if x > 1.5 else (3 if x > 1 else (2 if x > 0.5 else (1 if x > 0.25 else (0.5 if x > 0 else (-4 if x < -1.5 else (-3 if x < -1 else (-2 if x < - 0.5 else (-1 if x < -0.25 else (-0.5 if x < 0 else 0)))))))))
data['ConfirmedCasesPctChangeOrdinalCat'] = data['ConfirmedCasesPctChange'].apply(conditionOrdinal)
data['ConfirmedDeathsPctChangeOrdinalCat'] = data['ConfirmedDeathsPctChange'].apply(conditionOrdinal)

Corellation¶

https://www.dummies.com/education/math/statistics/how-to-interpret-a-correlation-coefficient-r/

Threshold 0.6 (https://towardsdatascience.com/are-you-dropping-too-many-correlated-features-d1c96654abe6)

Threshold 0.7 According to Tabachnick & Fidell (1996) the independent variables with a bivariate correlation more than 0.70 should not be included in multiple regression analysis.

Exactly –1. A perfect downhill (negative) linear relationship

–0.70. A strong downhill (negative) linear relationship

–0.50. A moderate downhill (negative) relationship

–0.30. A weak downhill (negative) linear relationship

  1. No linear relationship

+0.30. A weak uphill (positive) linear relationship

+0.50. A moderate uphill (positive) relationship

+0.70. A strong uphill (positive) linear relationship

Exactly +1. A perfect uphill (positive) linear relationship

Remove outliers¶

There are many outliers, sometimes there is a day increase of new cases more than 20 000% etc.

Three standard deviations from the mean is a common cut-off in practice for identifying outliers in a Gaussian or Gaussian-like distribution.

The values are not cut off but replaced with the +- 3 standard deviations.

https://datascience.stackexchange.com/questions/60714/how-can-i-replace-outliers-with-maximum-non-outlier-value

# calculate summary statistics https://machinelearningmastery.com/how-to-use-statistics-to-identify-outliers-in-data/
data_mean, data_std = np.mean(data['ConfirmedCasesPctChange']), np.std(data['ConfirmedCasesPctChange'])
# identify outliers - 3 Standard Deviations from the Mean
cut_off = data_std * 3
lower, upper = data_mean - cut_off, data_mean + cut_off

3.10. Time Shift¶

The impact of the measure is delayed. We need to find the best fitting delay.

The target is shifted from 0 to 40 days.¶

In [47]:
def day_shift_target(df: pd.DataFrame, days_shift: int, original_target: str, new_target: str) -> pd.DataFrame:
    df[new_target] = df.groupby('CountryRegionCode')[original_target].shift(days_shift)
    return df
In [48]:
delay_confirmed_cases = range(40)
delay_confirmed_deaths = range(40)
target_confirmed_cases = []
target_confirmed_deaths = []
for delay in delay_confirmed_cases:
    new_target = 'ConfirmedCasesPctChange' + str(delay) #ConfirmedCasesPctChangeOrdinalCat
    target_confirmed_cases.append(new_target)
    data = day_shift_target(data, -delay, 'ConfirmedCasesPctChange', new_target)
for delay in delay_confirmed_deaths:
    new_target = 'ConfirmedDeathsPctChange' + str(delay) #ConfirmedDeathsPctChangeOrdinalCat
    target_confirmed_deaths.append(new_target)
    dataDeaths = day_shift_target(dataDeaths, -delay, 'ConfirmedDeathsPctChange', new_target)  
dataShift = data.dropna(subset=[target_confirmed_cases[-1]]) # Drop all nans created because of time shift
dataDeathsShift = dataDeaths.dropna(subset=[target_confirmed_deaths[-1]]) 

/opt/anaconda3/lib/python3.7/site-packages/ipykernel_launcher.py:2: SettingWithCopyWarning: 
A value is trying to be set on a copy of a slice from a DataFrame.
Try using .loc[row_indexer,col_indexer] = value instead

3.11. Time Shift: The function for fitting¶

The function expect positive intercept (the number of new cases in increasing) and negative impact of strigency index (the number of new cases is decreasing by government responses).

In [49]:
import numpy as np
from scipy.optimize import curve_fit
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score

3.12. Time Shift: Fitting the different time shifts¶

The shifted targets from 3.10. are fitted to formula from 3.11.

In [50]:
delay_scores_confirmed_cases = {}
delay_scores_confirmed_deaths = {}
cases_popt = {}
deaths_popt = {}
X = dataShift[['StringencyIndex']].values #predictors + tempCutsCols
Xdeaths = dataDeathsShift[['StringencyIndex']].values #predictors + tempCutsCols
for target in target_confirmed_cases:  
    y = dataShift[target].values
    #mul_lr = LogisticRegression( 
    #    multi_class='multinomial', 
    #    solver='newton-cg', 
    #    fit_intercept=True 
    #)
    mul_lr = LinearRegression()
    mul_lr.fit(X, y)
    #y_rf = mul_lr.predict(data[['StringencyIndex']])
    delay_scores_confirmed_cases[target] = mul_lr.score(X, y)#r2_score(y, y_rf)
    cases_popt[target] = mul_lr.coef_
for target in target_confirmed_deaths:
    y = dataDeathsShift[target].values
    #mul_lr = LogisticRegression( 
    #    multi_class='multinomial', 
    #    solver='newton-cg', 
    #    fit_intercept=True 
    #)
    mul_lr = LinearRegression()
    mul_lr.fit(Xdeaths, y)
    #y_rf = mul_lr.predict(dataDeaths[['StringencyIndex']])
    delay_scores_confirmed_deaths[target] = mul_lr.score(Xdeaths, y) #r2_score(y, y_rf)
    deaths_popt[target] = mul_lr.coef_

3.13. Time Shift: Evaluation¶

R-squared is a goodness-of-fit measure for linear regression models. This statistic indicates the percentage of the variance in the dependent variable that the independent variables explain collectively. The larger the R2, the better the regression model fits your observations.

It shows that the impact of government responses is:

  • 6 days delayed for new case
  • 19 days delayed for deaths

3.15. Shift the target for modeling¶

In [60]:
# Keep just the right shifted ordinal column
target_confirmed_cases.remove(best_fitting_delay_confirmed_cases)
data = data.drop(target_confirmed_cases, axis=1)
target_confirmed_deaths.remove(best_fitting_delay_confirmed_deaths)
dataDeaths = dataDeaths.drop(target_confirmed_deaths, axis=1)
# Shift the categorical column
data['ConfirmedCasesPctChangeCat7'] = data.groupby('CountryRegionCode')['ConfirmedCasesPctChangeCat'].shift(-7)
dataDeaths['ConfirmedDeathsPctChangeCat19'] = dataDeaths.groupby('CountryRegionCode')['ConfirmedDeathsPctChangeCat'].shift(-19)
data = data.dropna(subset=['ConfirmedCasesPctChangeCat7'])
dataDeaths = dataDeaths.dropna(subset=['ConfirmedDeathsPctChangeCat19'])

dataDeaths['ConfirmedDeathsPctChangeCatBinary19'] = dataDeaths['ConfirmedDeathsPctChangeCat19'].apply(condition)

### Linear Regression (positive)
In [70]:
minus_predictors = []
for predictor in predictors:
    data[predictor + '_minus'] = - data[predictor]
    minus_predictors.append(predictor + '_minus')
    
dataTrain['tempCuts_(-60.001, -10.0]_minus'] = - pd.to_numeric(data['tempCuts_(-60.001, -10.0]'], downcast='signed')
dataTrain['tempCuts_(-10.0, 0.0]_minus'] = - pd.to_numeric(data['tempCuts_(-10.0, 0.0]'], downcast='signed')
dataTrain['tempCuts_(0.0, 10.0]_minus'] = - pd.to_numeric(data['tempCuts_(0.0, 10.0]'], downcast='signed')
dataTrain['tempCuts_(10.0, 20.0]_minus'] = - pd.to_numeric(data['tempCuts_(10.0, 20.0]'], downcast='signed')
dataTrain['tempCuts_(20.0, 30.0]_minus'] = - pd.to_numeric(data['tempCuts_(20.0, 30.0]'], downcast='signed')
dataTrain['tempCuts_(30.0, 60.0]_minus'] = - pd.to_numeric(data['tempCuts_(30.0, 60.0]'], downcast='signed')
modified_tempCutsCols = ['tempCuts_(-60.001, -10.0]', 'tempCuts_(-10.0, 0.0]', 'tempCuts_(0.0, 10.0]_minus', 'tempCuts_(10.0, 20.0]_minus', 'tempCuts_(20.0, 30.0]_minus', 'tempCuts_(30.0, 60.0]_minus']

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from matplotlib import pyplot
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

#regr = RandomForestRegressor(max_depth=10, random_state=42)
#X = data[predictors + ['tempC', 'humidity']]
#y = data['ConfirmedCasesPctChange6'].values
#regr.fit(X, y)
#importance = regr.feature_importances_


parametergrid= {"max_depth":(5, 6, 7), "n_estimators": (25, 50, 75, 100, 125)}
clf = GridSearchCV(RandomForestRegressor(random_state=42), parametergrid)
#regr = RandomForestRegressor(max_depth=10, random_state=42)
X = dataTrain[predictors + ['tempC', 'humidity']]
y = dataTrain['ConfirmedCasesPctChange7'].values
#regr.fit(X, y)
clf.fit(X, y)
print(clf.best_params_)
importance = clf.best_estimator_.feature_importances_

importance_p = list(zip(predictors + ['tempC', 'humidity'], importance))
imp_sorted = sorted(importance_p, key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=False)
pyplot.figure(figsize=(20,10))
pyplot.barh([x[0] for x in imp_sorted], [x[1] for x in imp_sorted])
pyplot.show()

{'max_depth': 5, 'n_estimators': 125}
